Product name: Vintage Queen Anne Style Bar Liquor Cabinet
Description:
This amazing piece is a Queen Anne style antique liquor cabinet from England. It was crafted there sometime around the year 1960. From parties to just an evening drink, this bar will serve you and your family in style for many years to come!
The wood used is walnut which has a stunning, wispy grain and light color. Enhancing the wood are stunning brass hinges and escutcheons that are elaborately engraved. Not something you see much of today! These brass pieces combined with the Queen Anne legs and wood carvings on the apron and top provide stunning elegance to this piece that is sure to attract attention.
Inside this antique liquor cabinet is a good amount of storage space. The top houses two removable glass shelves with a mirrored interior. There is a mirrored pull out shelf as well which is used for mixing drinks. the doors have four small shelves with brass rails on them. This bar also retains four of its six original olive pins. The bottom has a removable wooden shelf on the left and a large open section on the right. Great for storage of all kinds of bottles etc! Both doors lock and one key remains with the piece.
The cabinet remains in very good condition today. The key is a little finicky on the locks, sometimes you have to jiggle it or turn it twice to get them to work. There is a light inside the top but it would need to be replaced with one wired for US circuits. The interior has some light surface marks throughout as well. You will find small wear marks here and there as you would expect from something of this age, but nothing that detracts from the piece. It is sturdy and strong. This antique liquor cabinet is a great piece for storage and serving of drinks and would make a great addition to any space!
Overall dimensions:  35.25" w x 18" d x 64.25" h

Product name: Argus Seventy-five Camera Bakelite Body Vintage 1950's, Display Camera
Description:
This vintage 1950's Argus Seventy-five camera with a bakelite body. 
It was made in the USA from 1949 to 1964. This vintage camera is untested and I do not know if it still works. The body and interior are in very good used vintage condition.
Description from camera-wiki.org:
Pseudo TLR, produced by Argus in the USA, beginning in 1949.
The main body was molded from plastic (perhaps bakelite), while the film door is a painted metal casting. The front panel and viewfinder hood are in a contrasting satin-finish metal. A cloth neckstrap is permanently attached to the top of the body.
Images were 6x6cm on 620 film. While essentially a simple camera, it did feature double-exposure prevention, as well as a clever reminder when the film has been wound: A red-painted shutter blade is visible through the taking lens only after the shutter is cocked. Frame spacing relied on a simple red window, however.
The lens was branded as a 75mm Lumar, and was a single meniscus element in front of a fixed aperture of approximately f/11. Next to the shutter release, a small slider selected between "Inst" (instant) and "Time" (actually bulb).
A standard Argus Seventy-Five kit would typically have included a leather protective case, flashbulb holder (mounted with two pins 1-3/16" apart), and a slip-on accessory "portrait" lens to focus in the 3 to 4 foot range.
The final version of the Seventy-Five in production until 1964 received a modest redesign of its graphics, becoming the Argus 75. Argus also offered two higher-specification variations on the Seventy-Five, adding a focusable lens: the Argus 40 and the Argus Super Seventy-Five.
Owners hoping photograph with a Seventy-Five using currently-available 120 film will find that a 620 take-up spool is required. It is impossible to fit a 120 spool into the take-up compartment, as its dimensions are too small in all directions. However, a fresh roll of 120 can just barely be squeezed into the supply compartment, perhaps with some trimming down of the spool flanges.

Product name: Ukrainian Egg Dyes - Set of 6 Refill Dyes
Description:
Set of 6 Ukrainian egg dyes in yellow, orange, scarlet, light blue, light green, and black. This is a refill set of dyes for the starter-size Ukrainian egg decorating kit. These six colors are the most popular and commonly used in making pysanky.
These NON-EDIBLE dyes are similar to those used on textiles. They are more vivid than standard supermarket easter egg dyes, creating the brilliant contrasting colors so often used on modern pysanky and batik eggs. (See photo above, but note that some colors pictured are only available in my larger dye refill kit.)
Each of these dye packets makes 1 - 1/4 cup of non-edible, water-soluble dyeing solution. They have been approved by a licensed toxicologist as non hazardous to health when used as directed. 
For best results, you will need distilled water, white vinegar, and containers for mixing and storing the solutions -- wide mouth glass pint jars with tight sealing lids work well. The solution will last a long time if kept sealed and stored in a cool, dry place. I tend to add an extra tablespoon of white vinegar to compensate for evaporation if my dyes have been sitting for more than a few months. All needed instructions are included on the dye packets.
Ukrainian eggs made from these colorful dyes will stay brilliant and attractive for many years to come. To prevent fading, be sure to store finished eggs away from windows and direct sunlight.
For edible egg dyes, please visit: 
www.etsy.com/shop/UkrainianEggSupplies?section_id=11329401&ref=shopsection_leftnav_4

About us
Founded in Berlin early 2004, Savage Wear designs and creates high-quality, eccentric and fancy latex clothing for parties and shows, but also suitable for daily use. The fashionable aspect is important for us, as well as fulfilling customer dreams.
With love we design and manufacture all products in our studio in the heart of Berlin. In our designs we value the perfect fit and the first-class workmanship. Our extensive range of extravagant ladies' clothing is completed by fashionable outfits for gentlemen.
At Savage Wear the customer takes center stage. We at Savage Store are personally at your disposal for browsing, trials and fittings with a professional, individual consulting.
Dream style in your mind? We realize latex dreams!
The quality of Savage-Wear
We use quality latex from the well-known English company 4D-Rubber. The material is available in a wide range of colours and thicknesses. We mostly use latex in 0.35 mm and 0.6 mm thickness; in our opinion it provides the best combination of elasticity and strength. Custom orders can also be made in different thicknesses.
All our garments are glued, so the seams will keep their flexibility. We pay attention to all details as well as strengthening the rim. With the right care, you will have fun with your outfits for a real long time!
